    "slug": "lrat",
    "gene_name": "LRAT",
    "inheritance_pattern": "autosomal recessive",
    "disease_category": null,
    "status": "published",
    "full_name": "Lecithin retinol acyltransferase",
    "patient_population": "Fewer than 100 known",
    "treatment_status": "Clinical trial of drug intervention.",
    "eye_health_strategies": "—",
    "plain_english_summary": "Mutations in LRAT can cause juvenile retinitis pigmentosa and other early-onset retinal dystrophies. LRAT is an enzyme central to the retinoid (visual) cycle that regenerates the light-sensing chromophore in the eye. When LRAT function is impaired, the eye cannot produce enough functional chromophore, leading to retinal degeneration. Because the pathway is well understood, LRAT has been a target for drug and gene therapies."
  },
