    "status": "published",
    "full_name": "Phosphodiesterase 6B",
    "patient_population": "Unknown",
    "treatment_status": "—",
    "eye_health_strategies": "Lutein.",
    "plain_english_summary": "The PDE6B gene carries instructions for making part of a protein complex called cGMP-PDE, found in the light-sensing tissue at the back of the eye. PDE6B is part of the phototransduction cascade that converts light into the visual signals sent to the brain, which is especially important for low-light vision. Mutations disrupt this process and lead to progressive retinal degeneration."
  },
